  "prompt": "The current year is 2014. Why is this the 21st century and not the 20th century?",
  "response": "Great question! The numbering of centuries can indeed be a bit confusing. Here's why the year 2014 falls in the **21st century** rather than the **20th century**:\n\n### **How Centuries Are Numbered**\n\n1. **Start Point**: The first century began with the year **1** and ended with the year **100**.\n2. **Subsequent Centuries**: \n   - The **2nd century** spanned from **101** to **200**.\n   - The **3rd century** covered **201** to **300**, and so on.\n3. **Applying This to the 20th and 21st Centuries**:\n   - The **20th century** started on **January 1, 1901**, and ended on **December 31, 2000**.\n   - The **21st century** began on **January 1, 2001**, and will end on **December 31, 2100**.\n\n### **Common Misconception**\n\nMany people assume that the century number corresponds directly to the \"00\" years. For example, thinking that the year **2000** is the start of the 21st century. However, since there was **no year 0** in the Gregorian calendar, each new century starts **one year after** the century's \"00\" year.\n\n### **Quick Reference:**\n\n- **19th Century**: 1801\u20131900\n- **20th Century**: 1901\u20132000\n- **21st Century**: 2001\u20132100\n\n### **Example:**\n\n- **Year 1999** is in the **20th century**.\n- **Year 2000** is also in the **20th century**.\n- **Year 2001** is the first year of the **21st century**.\n- **Year 2014** falls within the **21st century**.\n\n### **Why It Matters**\n\nUnderstanding this helps in historical contexts, academic discussions, and even everyday references to time periods. It ensures clarity when discussing events, especially those that span century boundaries.\n\n---\n\nI hope this clarifies why we're currently in the 21st century!",
